# Consumer Transaction Analysis

**Analyst:** Mohit Das | MSc Economics, GIPE Pune  
**Tool:** MySQL (analysis) 
**Period:** January 2023 – December 2024

---

## About

This project analyses 5,000 retail transactions across Indian cities to
surface patterns in revenue, customer behaviour, and product returns. The
analysis was written in SQL and visualised as an interactive dashboard.

The approach mirrors how a business analyst or data team would handle
transactional data — cleaning and validating first, then answering
business questions that drive decisions on product mix, payment
infrastructure, and customer retention.

The analysis answers:

- Which product categories drive the most revenue, and which have the
  highest return rates?
- How has revenue grown year-over-year across categories?
- Which cities and states contribute the most to total sales?
- What does payment mode adoption look like across transactions?
- Which customers are Champions, Loyal, or At-Risk based on RFM logic?
- Are there day-of-week patterns in spending behaviour?

---

## Data Source

**Dataset:** [Pan-Indian Consumer Transaction Dataset](https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/kumarperiya/pan-indian-consumer-transaction-dataset) — Kaggle

**File:** `Transactions.csv`  
**Rows:** 5,000 transactions  
**Date Range:** January 2023 – December 2024  
**Unique Customers:** 1,446  
**Cities Covered:** 8  
**States Covered:** 7  

| Column | Description |
|---|---|
| `Txn ID` | Unique transaction identifier |
| `Date` | Transaction date |
| `Customer ID` | Anonymised customer identifier |
| `City` | City of transaction |
| `State` | State of transaction |
| `Category` | Product category (7 categories) |
| `Payment Mode` | UPI, Debit Card, Credit Card, Net Banking, Cash |
| `Amount (₹)` | Transaction value in INR (₹70 – ₹42,523) |
| `Returned` | Binary flag — 1 if returned, 0 if not |

**Product Categories:** Personal Care, Apparel, Books & Media,
Electronics, Sports, Food & Grocery, Home & Living

**Overall Return Rate:** 6.5%

---

## Analysis Modules (SQL)

The SQL script (`Consumer_Transaction_Analysis.sql`) runs eight
sequential analyses:

| Module | Method |
|---|---|
| Data Validation | Row counts, null checks, date range, invalid amounts |
| Monthly Revenue Trend | Revenue, transaction count, active customers by month |
| Category Performance | Revenue, return rate, average order value per category |
| Payment Mode Adoption | Transaction share % and average value per payment mode |
| City-wise Contribution | Revenue share by city and state (top 15) |
| Customer Segmentation | RFM proxy — Champions, Loyal, Potential, At-Risk, One-Time |
| Year-over-Year Growth | Category-level revenue growth, 2023 vs 2024 |
| Day-of-Week Pattern | Transaction volume and revenue by day |

---

## Limitations

- Dataset covers 8 cities and 7 states — findings are not
  representative of all-India retail behaviour.
- RFM segmentation uses a simplified frequency-monetary proxy; a full
  RFM model would incorporate a recency score relative to analysis date.
- Return reasons are not captured — return rate analysis identifies
  where returns are high but cannot explain why.
- Transaction amounts range up to ₹42,523 but outlier treatment was
  not applied; high-value transactions may skew average order values.
